05070nam a22007455i 9780812202373DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112004pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979576180  a97808122023737 a10.9783/97808122023732doi  a(DE-B1597)449096  a(OCoLC)759037222  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020102bisacsh04a307.7209385090141 aJones, Nicholas F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRural Athens Under the Democracy /cNicholas F. Jones. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Settlement -- t2. Society -- t3. Village -- t4. Dionysia -- t5. Realities -- t6. Images -- t7. Philosophy -- t8. Paradigms -- t9. Notes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMuch of the evidence—literary, historical, documentary, and pictorial—from ancient Athens is urban in authorship, subject matter, and intended audience. The result has been the assertion of an undifferentiated monolithic "Athenian" citizen regime as often as not identifiably urban in its lifestyle, preoccupations, and attitude. In Rural Athens Under the Democracy, however, Nicholas F. Jones undertakes the first comprehensive attempt to reconstruct on its own terms the world of rural Attica outside the walls during the "classical" fifth and fourth centuries B.C. What he finds is a distinctly nonurban (and nonurbane) order dominated by a traditional, predominantly agrarian society and culture.Jones relies heavily upon the relatively neglected epigraphic record from the rural countryside and villages, as well as posing new questions of the well-known urban writings of Athenian historians, essayists, and philosophers and occasionally following the lead of Hesiod's agrarian poem Works and Days. From these sources he gleans new findings regarding settlement patterns, argues for a heretofore unrecognized system of personal patronage, explores relations between villages and the town of Athens, reconstructs the "Agrarian" Dionysia in several of its more important dimensions, and contrasts the realities of rural Attic culture with their various representations in contemporary literary and philosophical writings by Aristophanes, Xenophon, Plato, and others.Building on Jones's previous publications on the ancient Greek city-state, Rural Athens Under the Democracy presents the first holistic examination of classical extramural Attica. He challenges the received view that ancient Athens in its heyday was marked by a uniform cultural, ideological, and conspicuously citified order and, in place of the perception of things rural as mere deficits in urbanity, proposes that we look at Attica outside the walls in its own right and in positive terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHistória antiga (aspectos sociaisxaspectos culturais)zÁticaxgrécia antiga. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aClassics.  aHistory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package World Historyz978311041347208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220237340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812202373423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812202373.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041347-2  Penn Press eBo